[## [SECTION: Step 8 — Prometheus Metrics (Components #46–48)]]

12
02:00:48,000 --> 02:00:54,000
Now let's build our Prometheus metrics module.
We'll put it in src/financial_rag/monitoring/metrics.py

13
02:00:54,000 --> 02:01:00,000
Prometheus is an open-source monitoring system.
It collects time-series metrics from your application.

14
02:01:00,000 --> 02:01:06,000
These metrics tell you how your system is performing.
How many queries per minute, how fast they are, and how many errors occur.

15
02:01:06,000 --> 02:01:12,000
First, imports. From prometheus_client, we import four metric types.
CONTENT_TYPE_LATEST for HTTP headers, Counter, Gauge, and Histogram.

16
02:01:12,000 --> 02:01:18,000
We also import generate_latest to produce the metrics output.

17
02:01:18,000 --> 02:01:24,000
Now let's define our metrics.
First, QUERY_TOTAL. This is a Counter, which only goes up.

18
02:01:24,000 --> 02:01:30,000
Counters are for monotonically increasing counts.
Total queries, total errors, total requests.

19
02:01:30,000 --> 02:01:36,000
QUERY_TOTAL has four labels. Analysis style, search type, agent type, and status.
Labels allow you to slice the data by different dimensions.

20
02:01:36,000 --> 02:01:42,000
Next, QUERY_LATENCY. This is a Histogram.
Histograms measure the distribution of values.

21
02:01:42,000 --> 02:01:48,000
We define buckets for latency. Point one seconds, point two five, point five, one, two point five, five, ten, and thirty seconds.

22
02:01:48,000 --> 02:01:54,000
QUERY_ERRORS is another Counter. It has a single label for error type.
This helps you see which errors are most common.

23
02:01:54,000 --> 02:02:00,000
Now Gauges. Gauges measure values that go up and down.
Unlike Counters which only increase.

24
02:02:00,000 --> 02:02:06,000
CHUNKS_TOTAL measures the number of chunks in the vector store.
It has a ticker label to track per-company counts.

25
02:02:06,000 --> 02:02:12,000
FILINGS_TOTAL measures the number of filings ingested.
With labels for ticker and filing type.

26
02:02:12,000 --> 02:02:18,000
INGESTION_TOTAL is a Counter for ingestion jobs.
With labels for ticker, filing type, and status.

27
02:02:18,000 --> 02:02:24,000
INGESTION_LATENCY is a Histogram for ingestion duration.
With longer buckets because ingestion takes more time than queries.

28
02:02:24,000 --> 02:02:30,000
Finally, cache metrics. CACHE_HITS and CACHE_MISSES are Counters.
These tell you how effective your Redis cache is.

29
02:02:30,000 --> 02:02:36,000
Now the helper functions.
record_query records metrics for a completed query.

30
02:02:36,000 --> 02:02:42,000
It increments the query total counter with the appropriate labels.
It observes the latency in the histogram.

31
02:02:42,000 --> 02:02:48,000
If the query failed, it also increments the error counter.
With the specific error type.

32
02:02:48,000 --> 02:02:54,000
record_ingestion does the same for ingestion jobs.
Increments the ingestion counter and observes latency.

33
02:02:54,000 --> 02:03:00,000
update_store_stats updates the gauge metrics.
Chunks total and filings total.

34
02:03:00,000 --> 02:03:06,000
These are gauges because they can go up or down.
As you delete filings or add new ones.

35
02:03:06,000 --> 02:03:12,000
Let me explain label cardinality. This is critical for production.

36
02:03:12,000 --> 02:03:18,000
Each unique combination of labels creates a new time series.
With three analysis styles, three search types, two agent types, and two statuses.

37
02:03:18,000 --> 02:03:24,000
That's three times three times two times two equals thirty-six series.
That's fine.

38
02:03:24,000 --> 02:03:30,000
But if you added a ticker label to QUERY_TOTAL, that would be dangerous.
If you queried ten thousand different tickers, you'd have ten thousand times thirty-six.

39
02:03:30,000 --> 02:03:36,000
That's three hundred sixty thousand time series.
Prometheus does not handle that well.

40
02:03:36,000 --> 02:03:42,000
That's why CHUNKS_TOTAL uses ticker as a label.
The number of tickers you ingest is bounded, maybe a few thousand.

41
02:03:42,000 --> 02:03:48,000
But QUERY_TOTAL does not use ticker.
Because queries could come for any ticker, unbounded.

42
02:03:48,000 --> 02:03:54,000
Now let's create the monitoring package __init__.py.
Open src/financial_rag/monitoring/__init__.py.

43
02:03:54,000 --> 02:04:00,000
We import get_metrics_output, record_ingestion,
record_query, and update_store_stats.

44
02:04:00,000 --> 02:04:06,000
Then we expose all four in __all__.

45
02:04:06,000 --> 02:04:12,000
Now anywhere in the application, you can import.
from financial_rag.monitoring import record_query, get_metrics_output

46
02:04:12,000 --> 02:04:18,000
Let me summarize the metric types and their use cases.

47
02:04:18,000 --> 02:04:24,000
Counters are for things that only increase.
Total queries, total errors, total cache hits.

48
02:04:24,000 --> 02:04:30,000
Gauges are for things that go up and down.
Number of chunks in the store, number of active connections.

49
02:04:30,000 --> 02:04:36,000
Histograms are for distributions.
Query latency, ingestion duration.

50
02:04:36,000 --> 02:04:42,000
The metrics module is complete.
Prometheus can now scrape your application for monitoring.


[## [SECTION: Step 9 — API Models (api/models.py)]]

51
02:04:42,000 --> 02:04:48,000
Now let's build our API models.
We'll put them in src/financial_rag/api/models.py

52
02:04:48,000 --> 02:04:54,000
These are Pydantic request and response models for the FastAPI layer.
They define the shape of data going in and out of the API.

53
02:04:54,000 --> 02:05:00,000
First, let's understand the two patterns worth highlighting.
StrEnum for API enumerations, and required fields with ellipsis.

54
02:05:00,000 --> 02:05:06,000
First, imports. From enum, we import StrEnum.
From typing, we import Any.

55
02:05:06,000 --> 02:05:12,000
From pydantic, we import BaseModel and Field.

56
02:05:12,000 --> 02:05:18,000
Now define our enums using StrEnum.
First, AnalysisStyle with three values. Analyst, executive, and risk.

57
02:05:18,000 --> 02:05:24,000
Second, SearchType with three values.
Similarity, MMR, and hybrid.

58
02:05:24,000 --> 02:05:30,000
Let me explain why we use StrEnum instead of regular Enum.

59
02:05:30,000 --> 02:05:36,000
With StrEnum, the enum value IS the string.
You don't need to use dot value in comparisons.

60
02:05:36,000 --> 02:05:42,000
And it serialises to the plain string in JSON automatically.
This makes API responses cleaner.

61
02:05:42,000 --> 02:05:48,000
Now the QueryRequest model.
This is the request body for the query endpoint.

62
02:05:48,000 --> 02:05:54,000
Question is a required string field.
Notice the ellipsis as the first argument to Field.

63
02:05:54,000 --> 02:06:00,000
The ellipsis means the field is required with no default.
Pydantic raises a validation error immediately if the request omits it.

64
02:06:00,000 --> 02:06:06,000
Ticker, filing type, and fiscal year are optional.
Analysis style defaults to analyst, search type defaults to similarity.

65
02:06:06,000 --> 02:06:12,000
Limit is optional but must be between 1 and 20 if provided.

66
02:06:12,000 --> 02:06:18,000
Now DocumentResponse.
This represents a single source chunk returned with a query response.

67
02:06:18,000 --> 02:06:24,000
It contains chunk ID, content, ticker, filing type,
fiscal year, section, similarity score, and extracted metrics.

68
02:06:24,000 --> 02:06:30,000
QueryResponse is the complete response from the query endpoint.
It includes the original question, the answer, analysis style, and search type.

69
02:06:30,000 --> 02:06:36,000
Agent type tells you whether the response came from the agent or query engine.
Latency in seconds, source documents, and any error.

70
02:06:36,000 --> 02:06:42,000
Now the ingestion models.
IngestionRequest is the request body for the ingest endpoint.

71
02:06:42,000 --> 02:06:48,000
It requires a ticker symbol.
Filing type defaults to 10-K, years defaults to 2 with a maximum of 5.

72
02:06:48,000 --> 02:06:54,000
IngestionResponse returns the results.
Ticker, filing type, filings found, chunks stored, success flag, skipped duplicates, and any error.

73
02:06:54,000 --> 02:07:00,000
Now the health models.
ServiceStatus represents the status of a single backing service.

74
02:07:00,000 --> 02:07:06,000
It has a boolean healthy flag and a details dictionary.
Details can contain version numbers, connection pool stats, or error messages.

75
02:07:06,000 --> 02:07:12,000
HealthResponse is the complete health check response.
It has an overall status string, version, and a services dictionary.

76
02:07:12,000 --> 02:07:18,000
Services can include database, cache, and embeddings.
Each with its own ServiceStatus.

77
02:07:18,000 --> 02:07:24,000
Finally, StatsResponse.
This is for the statistics endpoint.

78
02:07:24,000 --> 02:07:30,000
It contains ticker if filtered, total chunks, total filings,
embedding provider name, and embedding dimensions.

79
02:07:30,000 --> 02:07:36,000
Let me summarize the key patterns.

80
02:07:36,000 --> 02:07:42,000
First, StrEnum gives you string-based enums without dot value.
This is cleaner for API serialization.

81
02:07:42,000 --> 02:07:48,000
Second, Field with ellipsis makes fields required.
Pydantic validates this automatically before your handler runs.

82
02:07:48,000 --> 02:07:54,000
Third, optional fields use None as default.
This gives the API flexibility while keeping the contract clear.

83
02:07:54,000 --> 02:08:00,000
Our API models are complete.
The FastAPI routes can now use these for request validation and response formatting.


[## [SECTION: Step 10 — Dependency Injection (api/dependencies.py)]]

84
02:08:00,000 --> 02:08:06,000
Now let's build our FastAPI dependencies.
We'll put them in src/financial_rag/api/dependencies.py

85
02:08:06,000 --> 02:08:12,000
These are dependency injection functions used across route handlers.
All expensive objects are instantiated once at startup and reused.

86
02:08:12,000 --> 02:08:18,000
Dependency injection in FastAPI is a pattern where you declare what your route needs.
FastAPI automatically provides it from the dependency tree.

87
02:08:18,000 --> 02:08:24,000
First, imports. We need logging, and Annotated from typing.
From fastapi, we import Depends.

88
02:08:24,000 --> 02:08:30,000
From our application, we import QueryEngine, CacheClient,
get_cache_client, DatabaseClient, get_db_client, and VectorStore.

89
02:08:30,000 --> 02:08:36,000
Now we define module-level singletons.
_query_engine and _vector_store start as None.

90
02:08:36,000 --> 02:08:42,000
The get_vector_store function returns the singleton.
If it doesn't exist, it creates a new VectorStore instance.

91
02:08:42,000 --> 02:08:48,000
The get_query_engine function does the same for QueryEngine.
It first gets the vector store, then creates the engine.

92
02:08:48,000 --> 02:08:54,000
Why singletons? VectorStore and QueryEngine are expensive to create.
They load models, create embedding clients, and set up connections.

93
02:08:54,000 --> 02:09:00,000
Creating them once per request would be very slow.
So we create them once at startup and reuse them for every request.

94
02:09:00,000 --> 02:09:06,000
Now the FastAPI dependency functions.
These are used with Depends in route handlers.

95
02:09:06,000 --> 02:09:12,000
db_client yields the database client.
It simply calls get_db_client and returns it.

96
02:09:12,000 --> 02:09:18,000
cache_client yields the cache client.
Same pattern.

97
02:09:18,000 --> 02:09:24,000
query_engine yields the query engine singleton.
vector_store yields the vector store singleton.

98
02:09:24,000 --> 02:09:30,000
Now Annotated type aliases.
These make route signatures cleaner.

99
02:09:30,000 --> 02:09:36,000
DBClient is Annotated of DatabaseClient with Depends db_client.
CacheClient_ is Annotated of CacheClient with Depends cache_client.

100
02:09:36,000 --> 02:09:42,000
Engine is Annotated of QueryEngine with Depends query_engine.
Store is Annotated of VectorStore with Depends vector_store.

101
02:09:42,000 --> 02:09:48,000
Now a route signature can look like this.
async def query, then db colon DBClient.

102
02:09:48,000 --> 02:09:54,000
FastAPI automatically provides the database client.
No need to call get_db_client in every route.

103
02:09:54,000 --> 02:10:00,000
Now the startup and shutdown helpers.
These are called from the FastAPI lifespan context manager.

104
02:10:00,000 --> 02:10:06,000
initialise_dependencies runs once when the server starts.
First, we get the database client and call connect.

105
02:10:06,000 --> 02:10:12,000
Then we verify pgvector is installed.
If the extension is missing, we fail fast at startup.

106
02:10:12,000 --> 02:10:18,000
Next, we get the cache client and call connect.
Then we pre-warm the singletons.

107
02:10:18,000 --> 02:10:24,000
Calling get_vector_store and get_query_engine creates them now.
This makes the first request faster.

108
02:10:24,000 --> 02:10:30,000
shutdown_dependencies runs when the server shuts down.
It disconnects the database and cache clients gracefully.

109
02:10:30,000 --> 02:10:36,000
This ensures no connections are left hanging.
And all resources are properly cleaned up.

110
02:10:36,000 --> 02:10:42,000
Let me summarize the dependency injection flow.

111
02:10:42,000 --> 02:10:48,000
At startup, initialise_dependencies creates all connections.
It also creates the query engine and vector store singletons.

112
02:10:48,000 --> 02:10:54,000
During each request, the route handler declares its dependencies.
FastAPI calls the dependency functions and provides the instances.

113
02:10:54,000 --> 02:11:00,000
At shutdown, shutdown_dependencies closes everything gracefully.
No resources are leaked.

114
02:11:00,000 --> 02:11:06,000
Our dependencies module is complete.
FastAPI routes can now use these for clean, testable code.


[## [SECTION: Step 11 — Middleware (Components #42–45)]]

115
02:11:06,000 --> 02:11:12,000
Now let's build our API middleware.
We'll put it in src/financial_rag/api/middleware.py

116
02:11:12,000 --> 02:11:18,000
Middleware sits between the incoming request and your route handler.
It can modify requests, log information, enforce authentication, or rate limit.

117
02:11:18,000 --> 02:11:24,000
We have three middleware components.
Request logging, API key authentication, and rate limiting.

118
02:11:24,000 --> 02:11:30,000
First, imports. We need logging, time, uuid, and FastAPI components.
From slowapi, we import Limiter, the rate limit exceeded handler, and get_remote_address.

119
02:11:30,000 --> 02:11:36,000
From starlette middleware, we import BaseHTTPMiddleware.
And from our application, we import get_settings.

120
02:11:36,000 --> 02:11:42,000
First, create the rate limiter singleton.
It uses the client's IP address as the key, with a default limit of 100 requests per minute.

121
02:11:42,000 --> 02:11:48,000
The configure_limiter function attaches the limiter to the FastAPI app.
In development, it uses in-memory storage.

122
02:11:48,000 --> 02:11:54,000
In production with Redis available, it uses Redis as the backend.
This ensures rate limits are shared across multiple API replicas.

123
02:11:54,000 --> 02:12:00,000
Let me explain rate limiting in more detail.

124
02:12:00,000 --> 02:12:06,000
Rate limiting prevents a single client from overwhelming your API.
100 requests per minute is a sensible default.

125
02:12:06,000 --> 02:12:12,000
You can override this per route with a different limit.
For example, you might allow only 10 queries per minute for the expensive endpoint.

126
02:12:12,000 --> 02:12:18,000
Now the RequestLoggingMiddleware.
This logs every request coming into the API.

127
02:12:18,000 --> 02:12:24,000
It generates a unique request ID as a UUID.
This ID is stored in request.state so other middleware and handlers can access it.

128
02:12:24,000 --> 02:12:30,000
We log the start of the request with method, path, and client IP.
Then we measure the processing time.

129
02:12:30,000 --> 02:12:36,000
After the response is generated, we add two headers.
X-Request-ID so clients can trace their request through logs.

130
02:12:36,000 --> 02:12:42,000
And X-Process-Time with the duration in milliseconds.
Then we log the completion with status code and duration.

131
02:12:42,000 --> 02:12:48,000
This structured logging is critical for debugging.
You can grep your logs for a single request ID and see exactly what happened.

132
02:12:48,000 --> 02:12:54,000
Now the APIKeyMiddleware.
This provides optional API key authentication.

133
02:12:54,000 --> 02:13:00,000
It has an exempt paths set. Health, docs, redoc, and openapi.json are always allowed.
Load balancer health probes would fail without this.

134
02:13:00,000 --> 02:13:06,000
If API_KEY_ENABLED is False, the middleware does nothing.
If it's True, it checks the X-API-Key header.

135
02:13:06,000 --> 02:13:12,000
If the key matches the expected value from settings, the request continues.
If not, it returns a 401 Unauthorized response.

136
02:13:12,000 --> 02:13:18,000
Notice the response uses RFC 7807 format.
Type, title, status, detail, and instance fields.

137
02:13:18,000 --> 02:13:24,000
This is the standard error format for production APIs.
Clients can handle errors programmatically rather than parsing error strings.

138
02:13:24,000 --> 02:13:30,000
Now the exception handlers.
register_exception_handlers attaches handlers to the FastAPI app.

139
02:13:30,000 --> 02:13:36,000
The unhandled exception handler catches any unexpected error.
It logs the error with the request ID, then returns a 500 response.

140
02:13:36,000 --> 02:13:42,000
This prevents raw Python exceptions from reaching the client.
Which could leak sensitive information.

141
02:13:42,000 --> 02:13:48,000
The value error handler catches validation errors.
It returns a 422 Unprocessable Entity response.

142
02:13:48,000 --> 02:13:54,000
Both handlers use the same RFC 7807 format.
This gives clients a consistent error structure.

143
02:13:54,000 --> 02:14:00,000
Let me summarize the middleware order.

144
02:14:00,000 --> 02:14:06,000
Middleware order matters. FastAPI applies middleware in reverse registration order.
The first registered runs last.

145
02:14:06,000 --> 02:14:12,000
Typically you want authentication to run first, then logging, then rate limiting.
Check your server.py registration to ensure the intended order.

146
02:14:12,000 --> 02:14:18,000
Let me also highlight the request ID pattern.

147
02:14:18,000 --> 02:14:24,000
Every request gets a unique UUID injected into request.state.
All log lines in the lifecycle can include this ID.

148
02:14:24,000 --> 02:14:30,000
This enables end-to-end tracing across your logs.
You can trace a request from the moment it enters the API to the final response.

149
02:14:30,000 --> 02:14:36,000
Our middleware module is complete.
The API now has logging, authentication, rate limiting, and structured error responses.


[## [SECTION: Step 12 — Fix routes.py (Duplicate Write Bug)]]

150
02:14:36,000 --> 02:14:42,000
Now let's fix the routes.py file.
There was a duplicate write bug in the original implementation.

151
02:14:42,000 --> 02:14:48,000
When you added the analysis history recording, you may have left a second block.
Remove the duplicate and keep only one call to repo.record.

152
02:14:48,000 --> 02:14:54,000
Let's build the complete routes.py.
We'll put it in src/financial_rag/api/routes.py

153
02:14:54,000 --> 02:15:00,000
This file contains all the HTTP endpoints for the application.
Health check, query, ingestion, stats, and metrics.

154
02:15:00,000 --> 02:15:06,000
First, imports. We need logging, time, and UUID.
From fastapi, we import APIRouter, BackgroundTasks, HTTPException, and status.

155
02:15:06,000 --> 02:15:12,000
From our application, we import dependencies, models, and all the core components.
HTMLParser, TextParser, TextProcessor, SECIngestor, VectorStore, and more.

156
02:15:12,000 --> 02:15:18,000
Create the router instance.
router = APIRouter

157
02:15:18,000 --> 02:15:24,000
First, the health endpoint at GET slash health.
This returns the status of all backing services.

158
02:15:24,000 --> 02:15:30,000
We check the database by calling health_check.
If it succeeds, we mark it healthy and include details like PostgreSQL version.

159
02:15:30,000 --> 02:15:36,000
We check the cache by calling health_check on Redis.
If it succeeds, we mark it healthy with Redis version and memory usage.

160
02:15:36,000 --> 02:15:42,000
Then we determine the overall status.
Unhealthy if database is down, degraded if only cache is down, healthy if both are up.

161
02:15:42,000 --> 02:15:48,000
Now the query endpoint at POST slash query.
This is the main RAG endpoint for financial questions.

162
02:15:48,000 --> 02:15:54,000
We call engine.query with all the parameters from the request.
Analysis style and search type come from the enum values.

163
02:15:54,000 --> 02:16:00,000
After getting the result, we write to the audit trail.
We create an AnalysisRepository and call record.

164
02:16:00,000 --> 02:16:06,000
This stores the question, answer, latency, and source chunks.
If this fails, we log a warning but do not fail the request.

165
02:16:06,000 --> 02:16:12,000
We also record Prometheus metrics.
Total queries, latency, and success or failure.

166
02:16:12,000 --> 02:16:18,000
If the result has an error and no answer, we raise an HTTP exception.
Otherwise, we return the QueryResponse.

167
02:16:18,000 --> 02:16:24,000
Now the ingestion endpoint at POST slash ingest slash sec.
This triggers background ingestion of SEC filings.

168
02:16:24,000 --> 02:16:30,000
We use FastAPI's BackgroundTasks to run ingestion in the background.
The endpoint returns immediately with a 202 Accepted status.

169
02:16:30,000 --> 02:16:36,000
This is important because ingestion can take a long time.
Minutes for multiple years of filings.

170
02:16:36,000 --> 02:16:42,000
The background task downloads filings, parses HTML, chunks text, creates embeddings, and stores everything.

171
02:16:42,000 --> 02:16:48,000
The _ingest_background function does the actual work.
First, we create the HTML parser, text parser, and text processor.

172
02:16:48,000 --> 02:16:54,000
We use SECIngestor to list and download filings.
We save raw HTML to disk in case we need to re-process later.

173
02:16:54,000 --> 02:17:00,000
For each filing, we parse the HTML, clean the text, and create chunks.
Then we call store.ingest to embed and store everything.

174
02:17:00,000 --> 02:17:06,000
If a filing is a duplicate, we catch DuplicateFilingError and skip it.
We log progress and any errors.

175
02:17:06,000 --> 02:17:12,000
Now the stats endpoint at GET slash stats.
This returns global vector store statistics.

176
02:17:12,000 --> 02:17:18,000
Total chunks, total filings, embedding provider, and dimensions.
We also have a per-ticker version at GET slash stats slash ticker.

177
02:17:18,000 --> 02:17:24,000
Finally, the metrics endpoint at GET slash metrics.
This returns Prometheus metrics in text format.

178
02:17:24,000 --> 02:17:30,000
This endpoint is not included in the OpenAPI schema.
It's for Prometheus to scrape automatically.

179
02:17:30,000 --> 02:17:36,000
Let me summarize the key patterns in these routes.

180
02:17:36,000 --> 02:17:42,000
First, background tasks for long-running operations.
Ingestion returns immediately and runs in the background.

181
02:17:42,000 --> 02:17:48,000
Second, audit trail recording is non-fatal.
If the database is up but writing to analysis_history fails, we log and continue.

182
02:17:48,000 --> 02:17:54,000
Third, health checks for all dependencies.
The health endpoint lets load balancers know if the service is ready.

183
02:17:54,000 --> 02:18:00,000
Fourth, Prometheus metrics for monitoring.
Every query is tracked with labels for style, search type, and agent.

184
02:18:00,000 --> 02:18:06,000
Our API routes are complete.
The application now has a full REST API for financial RAG queries.


[## [SECTION: Step 13 — Application Server (Component #40)]]

185
02:18:06,000 --> 02:18:12,000
Now let's build the FastAPI application server.
We'll put it in src/financial_rag/api/server.py

186
02:18:12,000 --> 02:18:18,000
This is the entry point for the API.
It wires together all the components into a runnable application.

187
02:18:18,000 --> 02:18:24,000
The server handles startup and shutdown, CORS, middleware, exception handlers, and routes.

188
02:18:24,000 --> 02:18:30,000
First, imports. We need logging and contextlib.asynccontextmanager.
From typing, we import TYPE_CHECKING and AsyncGenerator.

189
02:18:30,000 --> 02:18:36,000
We import uvicorn as the ASGI server.
From fastapi, we import FastAPI and CORSMiddleware.

190
02:18:36,000 --> 02:18:42,000
From our application, we import dependencies, middleware, routes, and get_settings.

191
02:18:42,000 --> 02:18:48,000
Now the lifespan context manager.
This is the modern FastAPI pattern for startup and shutdown.

192
02:18:48,000 --> 02:18:54,000
It replaces the deprecated on_event startup and shutdown decorators.
Everything before the yield runs at startup.

193
02:18:54,000 --> 02:19:00,000
At startup, we log the application name, version, and environment.
Then we call initialise_dependencies.

194
02:19:00,000 --> 02:19:06,000
This connects the database, verifies pgvector, connects Redis, and pre-warms the singletons.
If any of this fails, the app fails to start. Fail fast.

195
02:19:06,000 --> 02:19:12,000
The yield keyword is the boundary.
After yield, the application runs.

196
02:19:12,000 --> 02:19:18,000
At shutdown, we log and call shutdown_dependencies.
This disconnects database and Redis gracefully.

197
02:19:18,000 --> 02:19:24,000
Now the create_app factory function.
This builds and configures the FastAPI application.

19802:19:24,000 --> 02:19:30,000
We load settings and create the FastAPI instance.
Title, description, version, and OpenAPI URLs.

199
02:19:30,000 --> 02:19:36,000
Notice that docs_url, redoc_url, and openapi_url are only enabled when DEBUG is True.
In production with APP_ENV production, DEBUG is False.

200
02:19:36,000 --> 02:19:42,000
This disables Swagger UI, ReDoc, and the OpenAPI schema in production.
Prevents attackers from enumerating your API surface.

201
02:19:42,000 --> 02:19:48,000
We attach the lifespan to the app.
Now the startup and shutdown logic will run automatically.

202
02:19:48,000 --> 02:19:54,000
Now we configure middleware.
First, CORS middleware with allowed origins from settings.

203
02:19:54,000 --> 02:20:00,000
CORS stands for Cross-Origin Resource Sharing.
It controls which web domains can call your API.

204
02:20:00,000 --> 02:20:06,000
We add RequestLoggingMiddleware for request tracing.
We register exception handlers for consistent error responses.

205
02:20:06,000 --> 02:20:12,000
We configure rate limiting with configure_limiter.
In production, this uses Redis as a shared backend.

206
02:20:12,000 --> 02:20:18,000
Finally, we add APIKeyMiddleware for optional authentication.
And we include the router with all the endpoints.

207
02:20:18,000 --> 02:20:24,000
We add a root endpoint at slash.
It returns the service name, version, and docs URL if enabled.

208
02:20:24,000 --> 02:20:30,000
Then we create the module-level app instance.
This is what uvicorn imports and runs.

209
02:20:30,000 --> 02:20:36,000
Finally, the dev entrypoint.
This runs uvicorn with reload enabled when DEBUG is True.

210
02:20:36,000 --> 02:20:42,000
In production, you would run uvicorn directly.
Without the reload flag for better performance.

211
02:20:42,000 --> 02:20:48,000
Let me summarize the middleware order.

212
02:20:48,000 --> 02:20:54,000
Middleware order matters. FastAPI applies middleware in reverse registration order.
The first registered runs last.

213
02:20:54,000 --> 02:21:00,000
Our order is. CORS first, then request logging, then rate limiting, then API key auth.
This means auth runs first on each request.

214
02:21:00,000 --> 02:21:06,000
Let me also highlight the lifespan pattern.

215
02:21:06,000 --> 02:21:12,000
The yield keyword is the key. Everything before yield is startup.
Everything after yield is shutdown.

216
02:21:12,000 --> 02:21:18,000
If startup fails, the app never starts.
This is correct behavior. Fail fast, don't run with missing dependencies.

217
02:21:18,000 --> 02:21:24,000
And docs are disabled in production.
Your OpenAPI schema is an attack surface. Disable it when not needed.

218
02:21:24,000 --> 02:21:30,000
Our application server is complete.
The entire system is now ready to run.


